BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 235.90 Tm (So here is the solution to all that pain. Spring Boot is a layer that sits on top of the regular Spring) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 220.70 Tm (framework and makes it easy to create applications that you can just run, straight away, with) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 205.50 Tm (almost no setup.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 185.30 Tm (Now there is one thing I really want to clear up, because people get confused. Spring Boot does) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 170.10 Tm (NOT replace Spring. Please remember that. You still write the same Spring code - the same) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 154.90 Tm (controllers, the same services. Boot just removes all the annoying setup that used to surround) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 139.70 Tm (them. Look at the stack on screen - your app sits on top, running on Spring Boot, which is built on) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 124.50 Tm (the Spring framework underneath. They work together.) Tj ET
