BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 656.50 Tm (Now let me peek under the hood at how auto-configuration actually works, because it is the) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 641.30 Tm (mechanism that replaced all that XML, and it is genuinely clever.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 621.10 Tm (When your app starts, Spring Boot runs through hundreds of little pre-written configuration recipes.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 605.90 Tm (And each recipe asks itself a yes-or-no question: 'given this particular project, should I switch on?') Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 590.70 Tm (Follow the flow on screen. First, it scans your project to see which libraries are present. Then it) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 575.50 Tm (checks conditions - little rules like 'only activate if this library is here, and only if the developer has) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 560.30 Tm (not already done this themselves'. Then it configures just the things that are actually needed.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 540.10 Tm (So the key word is conditional - each piece of setup only happens if it is relevant to your project.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 524.90 Tm (That is exactly why simply adding a starter is enough to switch on a whole feature. And here is a) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 509.70 Tm (thoughtful touch: if you decide to configure something yourself, Boot notices and politely steps) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 494.50 Tm (back, using yours instead of its default. It never fights you.) Tj ET
