0.720 0.720 0.760 rg 58.00 583.00 3.00 49.00 re f
BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.040 0.340 0.780 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 572.00 Tm (SAY \(read this aloud\)) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 556.00 Tm (Let's give a name to the thing doing all this work. The principle is Inversion of Control, and the part) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 540.80 Tm (of Spring that actually carries it out is called the IoC container - also known as the application) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 525.60 Tm (context. Think of it as a smart manager that runs the whole show.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 505.40 Tm (When your app starts, this manager scans for all your labelled classes, creates one instance of) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 490.20 Tm (each - by default just one, shared everywhere - figures out what each one needs, and injects those) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 475.00 Tm (needs automatically. Look at the diagram - the container is holding your controller, your service,) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 459.80 Tm (and your repository, all created and wired by it.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 439.60 Tm (So in our little app, the container creates the greeting service once, notices that the controller) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 424.40 Tm (needs a greeting service, and hands the same one over. And notice - you never wrote 'new') Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 409.20 Tm (anywhere. That is the 'inversion': normally your code is in charge of creating things, but here the) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 394.00 Tm (framework takes charge and assembles your objects for you. You just declare what you need and) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 378.80 Tm (let the manager handle the rest.) Tj ET
