BT /F2 15.00 Tf 0.100 0.100 0.120 rg 1 0 0 1 58.00 344.60 Tm (Slide 22 - Field, constructor & setter injection) Tj ET
0.040 0.520 1.000 rg 58.00 327.60 496.00 1.40 re f
BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.420 0.420 0.460 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 311.60 Tm (ON SCREEN) Tj ET
BT /F1 10.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 295.60 Tm (Two code panels - constructor injection \(recommended\) and field injection \(simplest\) - plus bullets on the) Tj ET
BT /F1 10.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 282.10 Tm (three styles.) Tj ET
0.720 0.720 0.760 rg 58.00 268.60 3.00 49.00 re f
BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.040 0.340 0.780 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 257.60 Tm (SAY \(read this aloud\)) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 241.60 Tm (There are three places Spring can inject a helper, and it is worth knowing the trade-offs, because) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 226.40 Tm (professionals have a clear preference.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 206.20 Tm (The recommended one, on the left, is constructor injection. The helper is passed in when the) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 191.00 Tm (object is built, and stored in a field marked 'final', meaning it can never change. The benefits are) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 175.80 Tm (real: the helper can never be missing or null, the class is easy to create in tests, and it is obvious) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 160.60 Tm (what the class depends on, just by looking at its constructor. This is the modern best practice.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 140.40 Tm (The simplest one, on the right, is field injection - you just put at-Autowired right on the field. It is the) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 125.20 Tm (shortest to write, which is why we use it in today's lab for clarity. But honestly, it is harder to test) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 110.00 Tm (and it hides what the class really needs, so in real projects you should prefer the constructor.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 89.80 Tm (And there is a third, setter injection, where Spring calls a setter method - that one is best for) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 74.60 Tm (optional helpers that might change later. So: constructor for required helpers, setter for optional) Tj ET
0.040 0.520 1.000 rg 58.00 70.60 3.00 193.00 re f
