BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.040 0.340 0.780 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 524.10 Tm (SAY \(read this aloud\)) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 508.10 Tm (Let's talk about the style our web service follows - it is called REST. The word is an abbreviation,) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 492.90 Tm (but forget the long form; here is the simple idea. You model your application as a set of 'resources') Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 477.70 Tm (- which are just nouns, things - and each thing has its own web address. Then you act on those) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 462.50 Tm (things using standard verbs.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 442.30 Tm (So a resource is a thing - a user, an order, a product, a greeting. It lives at an address like) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 427.10 Tm (slash-users-slash-42. And you act on it with an HTTP verb: GET to read it, POST to create one,) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 411.90 Tm (PUT to update it, DELETE to remove it. Nouns for the things, verbs for the actions. Very natural,) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 396.70 Tm (like a language.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 376.50 Tm (One more important property - REST is stateless. That means each request carries everything the) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 361.30 Tm (server needs to answer it, and the server keeps no memory of you between requests. Think of it) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 346.10 Tm (like ordering at a counter where they do not remember your last order - every order stands alone.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 330.90 Tm (That sounds limiting, but it is exactly what lets REST apps handle huge traffic and scale easily.) Tj ET
0.040 0.520 1.000 rg 58.00 315.70 3.00 214.40 re f
