BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 207.20 Tm (Let's connect those verbs to actual Spring code. Every interaction with a REST API uses an HTTP) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 192.00 Tm (verb that expresses your intent, and Spring gives each verb its own annotation that links a web) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 176.80 Tm (address to one of your Java methods.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 156.60 Tm (GET is for reading - it is 'safe', meaning it never changes anything - and it maps to at-GetMapping.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 141.40 Tm (POST is for creating new data - at-PostMapping. PUT is for updating - at-PutMapping. And) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 126.20 Tm (DELETE is for removing - at-DeleteMapping. Picking the right verb is part of good design - for) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 111.00 Tm (instance, because a GET never changes data, it is safe to retry it or cache it.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 90.80 Tm (Now, for today's lab, we only use at-GetMapping. Why just reading? Because reading is the) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 75.60 Tm (simplest possible case - you can test it just by typing a URL into your browser. The other three) Tj ET
